Avoid calling Engine.flush! in trap contextSince Ruby 2.0.0, We can't synchronize mutex in trap context.nnCurrently USR1 handler calls `Fluent::Engine.flush!` in trap handlern(main thread) and it attempts to lock mutexes.nnThis separates thread to call `Fluent::Engine.flush!` to avoid thatnlimitation.nn(Trap handlers run in main thread)nnSo this enables flushing via USR1 signal in Ruby 2.0.0 or later.n

Support guaranteed delivery from ForwardOutput to ForwardInputProtocols between ForwardOutput and ForwardInput are extended, adding `option` objectnto the end of the array, which is used to identify which chunks are written into the buffer.nAdditional behaviors of ForwardOutput and ForwardInput are as follows:nnForwardOutput sends data including `option` object which has object id of the chunknwith a value of `seq` key. After sending data, ForwardOutput waits for a responsenfrom InputForward in a certain time.n* If there is a response:n  * and if `ack` value of the response is same as `seq` value of sent data, it succeeded.n  * but if `ack` value and `seq` value are different, ForwardOutput sends the chunk again.n* If there is no response, ForwardOutput regards the target node as unavailablen  but does not send the chunk again because of compatibility.nnInputForward checks if received data includes `option` object. If it does, InputForwardnresponds to OutputForward after the chunk is written into the buffer (Engine.emit).nThe response has the `seq` value of the received data as a value of `ack` key, and isnserialized in the same way as received data.n
Fix an undefined variable namen->nnoden
Avoid deserializing an empty string which leads to EOFErrorWhen connection is closed by remote host, Socket#recv returns an emptynstring. So deserialize received data only when it is not empty.n

Add test cases with DummyEngineDriverIn test cases, DummyEngineDriver creates a TCP server in another thread and runs ForwardInput on it.nTo prevent ForwardInput from accessing Fluent::Engine by calling Engine.emit_streams,nDummyEngineDriver creates a dummy engine and sets Fluent::ForwardInput::Engine to it.n

Add config parameters for requiring in_forward to respond with ackThere are three parameters for ack (two are newly added, one is renamed):nn* extend_internal_protocoln  Whether to add an optional hash to the end of the sent data fromn  out_forward to in_forward. This is used for requiring ack responses orn  some future functions.nn* require_ack_responsen  Whether to require in_forward to respond with ack. If true, then  optional hash contains a chunk id.nn* ack_response_timeoutn  How many seconds out_forward waits for an ack response in.nnTo enable ack responses, set both extend_internal_protocol andnrequire_ack_response to true, and set ack_response_timeout to greaternthan zero.n

in_http: add support for 'add_remote_ip' config parameter.The 'add_remote_ip' configuration parameter allows the output filternto include the source IP address in a field called 'REMOTE_ADDR'.nnIt can be activated into the source as follows:nn<source>n  type httpn  port 9880n  add_remote_ipn</source>nnSigned-off-by: Eduardo Silva <eduardo@monkey.io>n

in_http: add support for 'cors_allow_origins' config parameter (#426).This patch enable a partial and optional CORS support. For clientsnthat want to talk directly to this source, it allows to set a whitenlist of Cross Origin clients through the validation of the HTTPnOrigin header. Usage:nn <source>n   type httpn   port 9880n   cors_allow_origins http://example.com, http://www.treasuredata.comn </source>nnThe new configuration key 'cors_allow_origins', allows to specify anwhite list of domains, they must be separated by coma.nnFor those request that do not pass the CORS filter, the service willnrespond with a '403 Forbidden' HTTP status code and close the connection.nnNote: the CORS validation is based on the HTTP request headers, for hencenis NOT secure.nnSigned-off-by: Eduardo Silva <eduardo@monkey.io>n

Fix to do `require` for required files straightforward, per files * Currently, all required files are loaded by `lib/fluent/load.rb` even for tests   * This file creates the implicit order of files to be loaded   * There's no explicit dependency definition, and there are many circular dependencies   * This situation is totally broken * Without this change, we can't run tests by `bundle exec rake test TEST=test/file.rb`   * Running whole tests consumes long time, and it's not acceptableThis change is to make straightforward dependency from all files to others.nWe can load any file in fluentd source code, make clean dependencies, andnalso can run each files itself to test it.n

Fix to do commit/rollback for 2 or more chunks at once * without this fix, some events will be written paritally if any chunks raise error in #append/#concat * it makes duplicated eventsBuffer#write will do: (method name was changed: #emit is method names for event routers)n* this method receives pairs of metadata and data to be written at oncen* append/concat these data to chunks (not committed)n* commit first chunkn  * if succeeded, then commit all (even if any following chunk raises error)n  * if failed, rollback allnnIn memory/file buffer, #commit is very lightweight operation and will NOT fail in most cases.nnThis change requires some additional internal APIs for buffers/chunksn* chunk status in general: this is required to make #write thread safen* keyword argument of #write: bulk and enqueuen  * #write method becomes much more complex, so bulk operation should be merged into an implementationn(we can't maintain two different/similar methods)n  * #write method enqueues chunks if needed, so :immediate mode should be implemented in same leveln* chunk_full_threshold configuration parameter to control chunk_size_full?n  * bulk and non-bulk #write were mergedn  * In non-bulk mode, it's too rare that written chunk content bytesize is same with limitationn

Reject chunks without timekey from candidates of destination of symlink (#1234)* Reject chunks without timekey from candidates of destination of symlinkrnrnsymlink feature is to link from symlink_path to the latest file chunk. Records with latest timekey will be appended into that file chunk.rnOn the other side, resumed file chunks might NOT have timekey, especially in the cases that resumed file chunks are generated byrnFluentd v0.12. These chunks will be enqueued immediately, and will be flushed soon.rnrnSo these files SHOULD NOT be a candidate of destination of symlink.rnrn* added a comment to show why chunks w/o timekey can be skippedrn

Run TailWatcher#on_notify before attaching triggersThis commit runs `TailWatcher#on_notify` before attaching `stat_trigger` and `timer_trigger` and prevents `TailWatcher#on_notify` from running in two different threads(main and event loop thread) at the same time.nnThis change fixes the `can't modify string; temporarily locked` error.nnI think fluentd v0.12 does not raise the `can't modify string; temporarily locked` error because it runs `stat_trigger` and `timer_trigger` after `TailInput#start` finishes and   thus `TailWatcher#on_notify` is not executed in two threads simultaneously.nnfluentd v0.12nin_tail.rbnn```rubyndef startn  @loop = Coolio::Loop.newn  refresh_watchersnn  @thread = Thread.new(&method(:run))nendnndef runn  @loop.runnendn```n

support multi workers in file bufferThis updated code handles path as:n* when working as single worker:n  * create buffer.*.log files under path if path is directory (or missing)n  * create files specified in path if path is filen* when working as multi worker:n  * create workerN directories under path if path is directory (or missing)n* create files #{path}/workerN/buffer.*.logn* and only worker_id=0 process resumes #{path}/buffer.*.log filesn* these files may exist when this multi-worker process was configured as a single worker servern  * raise error if path is filen* because there are no way to create multi-process safe directory tree / filesn

Always lock chunks first to avoid deadlockThis commit resolves https://github.com/fluent/fluentd/issues/1549.nnFor example, deadlock occurs by the following steps before this commit:nn1. input plugin thread receives multiple eventsn  (metadata_and_data.size > 1)n2. input plugin thread processes the first metadata_and_data elementn  and aquires the lock of chunk1 (chunk.mon_exit in Buffer#write)n3. enqueue thread aquires the lock of buffern  (synchronize in Buffer#enqueue_chunk)n4. enqueue thread tries to aquire the lock of buffern  (chunk.synchronize in Buffer#enqueue_chunk)n5. input plugin thread processes the second metadata_and_data elementn  and tries to aquire the lock of buffer (synchronize in Buffer#write_once)n

Issue 1726: Fix for in_tcp log corruption under load.The TCP input plugin shares a single buffer across all connections.  Under loadnthe buffer sometimes gets truncated.  The suspicion is that concurrentnconnections race to modify it.nnLong message is received.nShort message is received while the long message is still being parsed.nThe short message is parsed so the buffer will be truncated.nThe buffer, which now contains longmessagenshortn, is truncated by thenlength of the short message.  It is now longm.nAnother message arrives.  Now the buffer is longmanothern, which does notnparse.nThe whole buffer is thrown away and subsequent messages are received andnhandled as usual.nEventually the pattern repeats.nnThe fix is to use a per-connection buffer.n

in_tail: Prevent the thread-unsafe method from being called concurrentlyEssentially there is a concurrency bug in the implementation of `in_tail`.nnWhile `IOHandler` is not designed to be thread-safe, its method `on_notify`ncan be called by multiple threads concurrently. In particular, consider thenfollowing situation:nn 1. TailInput calls `on_notify` on detach/shutdown (main thread)n 2. In the same time, StatWatcher triggers `on_notify` on filesystem eventsn(eventloop thread)nnThis patch fixes this issue by introducing a mutex, which should preventnmultiple threads from entering the critical session simultaneously.n

in_tail: Handle records in the correct order on file rotationThis is a fix for the events-emitted-in-the-wrong-order bug reported bynfluentd#1055. It turned out that this bug was a matter of the callingnorder of functions in TailWatcher.on_rotate().nnIn particular, when TailWatcher detects a log rotation and immediatelynfinds a new file, it performs the following steps:nn  1) Create a new TailWatcher for the new file.n* In this process, it reads the new file and emit its contents.n* All of this happens before proceeding to (2).n  2) Read the old file and emit its contents.nnSo naturally, newer log records (written to the new log file) will benemitted before older records in the archived log file.nnThis patch fixes it by enforcing flush of older log records beforenperforming the step (1).n

test: Fix random test failures in test/plugin/test_out_forward.rbI notice that the following test cases (which are supposed to test thenhandling of broken ack responses) are randomly failing on Travis CI:nn 1. 'a destination node not supporting responses by disconnection'n 2. 'a destination node not supporting responses by just ignoring'nnThe root problem is that, since the destination node gets labelled asnunavailable after an ack failure, there really shouldn't be any flushnattempt after the testing steps (or it will raise a NoNodesAvailablenexception).nnIn most environments, this possibility does not pose much problemsnbecause the test execution is sufficiently fast (so there is verynlittle space for an additional flush attempt to occur).nnBut since the CI server is known to become very slow from time to time,nwe need to take special care for it.n

output: Prevent flushing threads from consuming too much CPU.This fixes the CPU spike issue reported by several users.nnIf one flush thread sets the retry state, this makes other threadsnwait until the next retry time. This behaviour itself is fine and ok.nnHowever, in this case the `interval` variable has a meaningless valuenbecause `state.next_time` is behind the system time. And since thensleep call gets skipped in such a case (output.rb#L1343):nnsleep interval if interval > 0nnit effectively makes the waiting threads to consume the resourcenaggressively with busy loops.n

Use Strftime instead of Time#strftimeStrftime is faster than Time#strftime.nn```n$ bundle exec ruby t.rbnRehearsal -------------------------------------------------nTime#strftime   4.380378   0.835296   5.215674 (  5.219284)nStrftime2.861623   0.740209   3.601832 (  3.603956)n---------------------------------------- total: 8.817506secnnuser system  totalrealnTime#strftime   4.688617   0.847361   5.535978 (  5.539647)nStrftime2.691129   0.852342   3.543471 (  3.546031)n```nnUsing following benchmark script:nn```rubynrequire benchmarknrequire_relative ./lib/fluent/loadnnN = 1000nnformatter = Strftime.new('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%N %z')nnevent_times = []n1000.times don  event_times << Fluent::EventTime.new(Time.now.to_i, (rand * 10**9).to_i)nendnnBenchmark.bmbm do |x|n  x.report(Time#strftime) donN.times don  event_times.each do |event_time|nTime.at(event_time).strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%N %z')n  endnendn  endn  x.report(Strftime) donN.times don  event_times.each do |event_time|nformatter.exec(Time.at(event_time))n  endnendn  endnendn```n

in_http: Honor `keep_time_key` parameter in batch mode.The in_http plugin supports batch mode for sending multiple events inna single HTTP request. The problem is that in_http does not honor then`keep_time_key` option when processing those bulk-insertion requests.nnThis means that time key in each record gets discarded unconditionallynin batch mode. For example, the following request:nn$ curl -d '[{time:1514736000,key:foo}]' http://localhost/nnwill produces a log record:nn2018-01-01 01:00:00.000000000 +0900 : {key:foo}nneven if the `keep_time_key` option is enabled.nnThis patch fixes this issue by teaching in_http to honor the optionnvalue of its parser plugin instance.nnSigned-off-by: Fujimoto Seiji <fujimoto@clear-code.com>n

test/counter: Fix test failures on AppVeyor due to rounding errors.Evidently, Timecop.travel induces flogting-point errors to Time.now onnWindows environment:nn>>> Time.freeze(Time.parse('2016-09-22 16:59:59 +0900'))n>>> Timecop.travel(6)n>>> printf(#{Time.now.to_i}.#{Time.now.nsec}n)n1474531204.999999999nn... and this seems to be the major cause of the test failures on AppVeyor.nnThis patch fixes the issue by introducing a helper method `travel()` thatnallows to travel back/forward without such errors.nnSigned-off-by: Fujimoto Seiji <fujimoto@clear-code.com>n

test_out_file.rb: Fix test failures due to Zlib::DataError.AppVeyor CI tests are constantly failing due to Zlib-related exceptionsnlike below:nnError: test: append(FileOutputTest): Zlib::DataError: invalidndistance too far backnnThis is a very weird error, because the file seems to contain a properngzip-compressed data stream. In fact, by inserting the following codenbefore the failing line, I can confirm that the file itself is NOTnbroken:nnbytes = File.open(path).read   // Read the file being testednputs(Zlib::GzipReader.new(StringIO.new(bytes)).read)nnThe strong suspicion is that Ruby's Zlib wrapper (or its build onnAppVeyor) has a serious bug that corrupts file pointers passed tonGzipReader, thus it ends up reading garbage data.nnThis patch is my attempt to mitigate the issue by modifying the testnfunctions to pass bytes (rather than file objects) to GzipReader, andnit should protect zlib from read-time data corruptions.nnSigned-off-by: Fujimoto Seiji <fujimoto@clear-code.com>n

test_retry_state: Fix a test failure on AppVeyor with Ruby 2.3 (x86)This fixes 'check inf handling' test not to fail on AppVeyor CI anymore.nnSpecifically, in this test script, it is assumed that `0.1 * 2 ** 10.25`noverflows the float boundary and becomes an infinite number. This is notnquite true because the number is roughly 1.79e+307 and it's actually wellnbelow the upper boundary of double-precision floats.nnStill, even though the resulting number is within the maximum limit, thentest case passes on *most* environments because an overflow occursnwhile computing raw_interval():nndef raw_interval(num)n  @constant_factor.to_f * (@backoff_base ** (num))nendnnBut evidently this is not reliable among environments. So let's makenthe interval actually go over the boundary, instead of relying on annunreliable behaviour.nnSigned-off-by: Fujimoto Seiji <fujimoto@clear-code.com>n

Consider timezone when calculate timekeyBecause the timestamp of the midnight cannot be divisible by 86400 innlocaltime (JST). The timestamp of the midnight is divisible by 86400nonly in UTC. Therefore we must consider offset from UTC in localtime.nnFor example, at `2018-07-04 01:23:23 +0900`:nnIf timekey is 86400 and path template is `/log/%Y%m%d.log`.nIn previous version, extract path template to `/log/20180703.log`.nIn this version, extract path template to `/log/20180704.log`.nnFix #1986nnSigned-off-by: Kenji Okimoto <okimoto@clear-code.com>n

in_http: Fix ignored parser options problem on bulk insertionWhat used to happen is that options in the <parser> section get ignorednwhen we send events as a JSON array. This occurs because parser pluginsnare designed to handle a single hash value and do not generallly handlenan array input well.nnUntil now, we have tried to solve this issue by emulating the semanticsnof parser plugins in Fluent::Plugin::HttpInput (see 1afbfb1, 39f3a0dnand f560017c). However, this approach turned out to be error prone andnrather tedious.nnThis patch takes a different approach:nn - Whenever @parser is available, reuse @parser.convert_values() byn   manually applying it to each record in an input array.n - Otherwise, fall back to the current logic.nn... and should solve this class of issues.nnSigned-off-by: Fujimoto Seiji <fujimoto@clear-code.com>n

Keep `class` method to avoid error on Sigdump.dump.When stopping fluentd, sometime I get follwoing error message on stderr;nn```nUnexpected error undefined method `class' for #<Fluent::Plugin::RecordTransformerFilter::RubyPlaceholderExpander::CleanroomExpander:0x00007f7f1aca50d0>n  /opt/td-agent/embedded/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/gems/sigdump-0.2.4/lib/sigdump.rb:74:in `block in dump_object_count'n  /opt/td-agent/embedded/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/gems/sigdump-0.2.4/lib/sigdump.rb:73:in `each_object'n  /opt/td-agent/embedded/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/gems/sigdump-0.2.4/lib/sigdump.rb:73:in `dump_object_count'n  /opt/td-agent/embedded/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/gems/sigdump-0.2.4/lib/sigdump.rb:18:in `block in dump'n  /opt/td-agent/embedded/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/gems/sigdump-0.2.4/lib/sigdump.rb:136:in `open'n  /opt/td-agent/embedded/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/gems/sigdump-0.2.4/lib/sigdump.rb:136:in `_open_dump_path'n  /opt/td-agent/embedded/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/gems/sigdump-0.2.4/lib/sigdump.rb:14:in `dump'n  /opt/td-agent/embedded/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/gems/serverengine-2.0.7/lib/serverengine/server.rb:74:in `dump'n  /opt/td-agent/embedded/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/gems/serverengine-2.0.7/lib/serverengine/server.rb:112:in `block (2 levels) in install_signal_handlers'n  /opt/td-agent/embedded/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/gems/serverengine-2.0.7/lib/serverengine/signal_thread.rb:96:in `main'n```nnThis cause Sigdump.dump fails with CleanroomExpander because it willncall `class` method for all objects to gathering stats.nnThis patch just keep `class` method to avoid error.nnSigned-off-by: Tatsuki Sugiura <sugi@nemui.org>n

Fix plugin log time format if format is JSONThe time format for a plugin logger was out of sync with the parentnlogger, and the delegation of #time_format and #time_format= made itnimpossible to fix the plugin logger's time format without hacks.nnThis problem was not noticeable if the log format was text, becausentime formatting was delegated via #caller_line to the parent logger.nHowever, in the case of JSON output, the plugin logger's #format_timenmethod was called, yielding incorrectly-formatted timestamps.nnAdded tests for both text and JSON, and added tests for format changesnin general while I was in there.nnSigned-off-by: Owen Smith <owen@udacity.com>n

Moved `super` into the outside of a synchronized context.No need to call `super` in a synchronized context because TLSServer doesn't use the inner buffer(::IO::Buffer) of Coolio::IO.nInstead of using Coolio::IO's inner buffer, TLSServer has own buffer(`@_handler_write_buffer`). See also TLSServer#write.nActually, the only reason calling `super` here is call Coolio::IO#disable_write_watcher.nIf `super` is called in a synchronized context, it could cause a mutex recursive locking since Coolio::IO#on_write_completeneventually calls TLSServer#close which try to get a lock.nnSigned-off-by: Yuta Iwama <ganmacs@gmail.com>n
